Some of their demands include stopping outsourcing, decolonising education &amp; scrapping historical debt. CAPE TOWN - Finance minister Pravin Gordhan has accepted a memorandum from Fees Must Fall campaigners ahead of his Medium Term budget speech. More than 1,000 students and workers from different tertiary institutions have marched to Parliament today calling for free education. The hundreds of students and workers from various institutions have marched from the Cape Peninsula University of Technology's Cape Town campus to Parliament ahead of today's medium term budget speech. Protesters have been kept out of the parliamentary precinct by a heavy police presence and ring fencing. Some of their demands include stopping outsourcing, decolonising education and scrapping historical debt. #Fees2017 Gordhan signs memorandum but crowd is not happy with him leaving. @JustKoyana pic.twitter.com/wc46i9pIMI&mdash; EWN Reporter (@ewnreporter) October 26, 2016 #Fees2017 Gordhan signs memorandum but crowd is not happy with him leaving. @JustKoyana pic.twitter.com/wc46i9pIMI